{"id":"2002.05068","submitter":"Vincent Froese","authors":"Tomohiro Koana, Vincent Froese, Rolf Niedermeier","title":"The Complexity of Binary Matrix Completion Under Diameter Constraints","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.DS cs.DM","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We thoroughly study a novel but basic combinatorial matrix completion\nproblem: Given a binary incomplete matrix, fill in the missing entries so that\nevery pair of rows in the resulting matrix has a Hamming distance within a\nspecified range. We obtain an almost complete picture of the complexity\nlandscape regarding the distance constraints and the maximum number of missing\nentries in any row. We develop polynomial-time algorithms for maximum diameter\nthree based on Deza's theorem [Discret. Math. 1973] from extremal set theory.\nWe also prove NP-hardness for diameter at least four. For the number of missing\nentries per row, we show polynomial-time solvability when there is only one and\nNP-hardness when there can be at least two. In many of our algorithms, we\nheavily rely on Deza's theorem to identify sunflower structures. This paves the\nway towards polynomial-time algorithms which are based on finding graph factors\nand solving 2-SAT instances.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 12 Feb 2020 16:16:20 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 20 Oct 2022 09:32:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-10-21"}
